/-! ## Demo 9 ŌĆö `call <hash>` decoding

A program that issues a syscall by Murmur3 hash, then exits. Without a
hash table the decoder routes the call to `Syscall.unknown <hash>`,
whose default semantics sets `r0 := 0`. The program then exits with
that `r0`. This proves the `call` opcode (0x85) decodes and runs
cleanly ŌĆö required for any program that calls `sol_log_*`,
`sol_memcpy_*`, `sol_invoke_signed_*`, etc. -/

def callProgram : ByteArray := Ō¤©#[
  -- call 0x12345678  (some unknown syscall hash)
  0x85, 0x00, 0x00, 0x00, 0x78, 0x56, 0x34, 0x12,
  -- exit
  0x95, 0x00, 0x00, 0x00, 0x00, 0x00, 0x00, 0x00
]Ō¤®

example : Runner.runForExit callProgram = some 0 := by native_decide

/-! ## Demo 10 ŌĆö ELF with `.rodata` (Anchor/Pinocchio pattern)

A 378-byte ELF with four sections: null, `.text`, `.rodata`, `.shstrtab`.
The bytecode reads a constant out of `.rodata` (loaded at VA
`0x100000000`) and exits with it. This is the universal pattern across
Anchor/Pinocchio/native-Rust binaries ŌĆö the `.rodata` mapping is what
unblocks them.

```
  lddw r1, 0x100000000      ; pointer to .rodata
  ldxb r0, [r1 + 0]         ; read one byte
  exit                      ; r0 = 0x37 = 55
```
-/

